feed.title: Ocean Grove Nature Reserve
feed.subtitle: Originally known as Cuthbertson's Paddock, this reserve covers 143 hectares and represents one of the last remaining stands of native woodland on the Bellarine Peninsula.

entry.title: Wurmbea latifolia subsp. vanessae
entry.content: An unexpected find at the Reserve. Uncommon species; also of note is the late flowering time. Often flowering 'nancies' are one of the first signs of spring flowering from July/August. 2 pics with images of the same plant taken one day apart

entry.title: Thelymitra pauciflora s.s.
entry.content: Unusual creamy white coloured Thelymitra Pauciflora. Was seen in the company of the more usual coloured blueish-mauve T. pauciflora and also T. rubra. (2 pics.)

entry.title: Corybas incurvus
entry.content: 4 images of Slaty Helmet-orchids with flowers in various stages of development. Newly emerging flowers appeared in mid-July. 2 weeks later in early August the flowers were fully formed.

entry.title: Euproctis melanosoma
entry.content: The ID created a challenge. Males of this species, as featured in MOV 2 shows a white tuft end to the abdomen. This one has an orange colour tuft as well as a black upper body and stripes on the underside of the body. May eventually be found to be a different species. It got knocked off the sheet by a larger insect and played dead long enough to get a photo of the underside. Two additional images included to show the features.

entry.title: Proteuxoa sanguinipuncta
entry.content: Another difference from P. rubripunta is the tawny colour thorax on the P. sanguinipuncta.

entry.title: Proteuxoa rubripuncta
entry.content: Note that the spot, on the forewing, is red surrounded by black where as the P. sanguinipuncta has a black spot surrounded by red in similar location.

entry.title: Glyphipterix meteora, Lobelia pratioides
entry.content: A single Glyphipterix meteora moth. Other Glyphipterix meteora moths had been observed on Burchardia umbellata (Milkmaids) the previous day. Interesting to see a similar photo by Russell Best (below) in this Lobelia species list with the same moths, plus a beetle. As mentioned by Russell Best the moth appears to be feeding from below.

entry.title: Scopula rubraria
entry.content: Single moth flowing low and stopping constantly in the long grasses. Lighter coloured form to others on this page. I note Cathy's comments about the variability in colour of this species.

entry.title: Burchardia umbellata, Glyphipterix meteora
entry.content: Glyphipterix meteora moths enjoying the pollen on Burchardia umbellata (Milkmaids). Moth ID provided by Marilyn Hewish.
